In the [[Football at the 1994 Asian Games – Men's tournament|1994 Asian Games]], Uzbekistan were grouped with powerhouse [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]], [[Thailand national football team|Thailand]] and [[Malaysia national football team|Malaysia]], alongside [[Hong Kong national football team|Hong Kong]]. After a 4–1 victory over the Saudis, Uzbekistan followed up with a 5–0 victory over Malaysia and a 1–0 win over Hong Kong before winning the group with a 5–4 win against Thailand. In the quarter-finals, Uzbekistan defeated [[Turkmenistan national football team|Turkmenistan]] 3–0 to advance to the semi-finals where they faced [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]]. The Korean side included nine players that had already participated in the [[1994 FIFA World Cup]]; despite this, Uzbekistan shocked South Korea with a 1–0 victory to advance to the final, its first ever final since gaining independence from the Soviet Union.
In their final game against [[China national football team|China]], Uzbekistan defeated the Chinese 4–2 to capture its first and only Asian honor two years after its creation.<ref name="futbolgrad">{{cite web|url=http://www.futbolgrad.com/uzbekistan-remembering-miracle-1994/|title=Uzbekistan - Remembering the Miracle of 1994|website=Futbolgrad|date=25 August 2017|access-date=28 November 2021|archive-date=15 November 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211115052059/http://www.futbolgrad.com/uzbekistan-remembering-miracle-1994/|url-status=live}}</ref>

In the [[1996 AFC Asian Cup]], Uzbekistan was grouped with Japan, China and [[Syria national football team|Syria]], and were eliminated in the group stage. Uzbekistan's first-ever attempt to qualify for the World Cup was in [[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)|1998]]. Grouped with [[Yemen national football team|Yemen]], [[Cambodia national football team|Cambodia]] and [[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia]] in the first stage, Uzbekistan won every match except for the away fixture against Indonesia. Shortly after, the Uzbeks played [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]], [[Japan national football team|Japan]] and the [[United Arab Emirates national football team|UAE]], and failed to qualify for the tournament.{{Citation needed|date=March 2025}}

=== 2000s ===
The [[2000 AFC Asian Cup]] saw the Uzbeks with Japan, Saudi Arabia and [[Qatar national football team|Qatar]], gaining only a point against the latter with a draw. Uzbekistan participated in the [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC first round|first round]] in order to qualify for the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]] in Japan and South Korea, and eventually made the [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC second round|second round]]. The group contained [[China national football team|China]], the [[United Arab Emirates national football team|UAE]], [[Oman national football team|Oman]] and [[Qatar national football team|Qatar]], and the Uzbeks were unable to make any major breakthrough in the second round, losing twice to the UAE, and suffering two away defeats to China and Oman. An away draw to Qatar confirmed Uzbekistan's failure to qualify, despite a late win over already qualified China in the final match.{{Citation needed|date=March 2025}}

Uzbekistan failed to make further impact on the continental stage until they reached the last eight of the [[2004 AFC Asian Cup|2004 Asian Cup]], topping their group after winning all matches, where they were beaten by [[Bahrain national football team|Bahrain]] after a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2025}} The country would eventually defeat [[Iraq national football team|Iraq]] in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC second round#Group 2|second qualifying round]] for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]] in [[Germany]], with goals from [[Maksim Shatskikh]] and [[Alexander Geynrikh]] sending them through to the last eight. They were knocked out in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC fourth round|final stage]] of the [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)|Asian qualification]] to the 2006 World Cup after losing on the [[away goals rule]] to [[Bahrain national football team|Bahrain]]. The result was subject to controversy as three games were played; the first, a 1–0 win for Uzbekistan was wiped out after FIFA declared the result void after a mistake by [[Toshimitsu Yoshida]], a Japanese referee.<ref>{{cite web|title=Uzbekistan and Bahrain to play it again|url=http://www.espnfc.com/story/341697/uzbekistan-and-bahrain-to-play-it-again|publisher=ESPN|access-date=13 July 2016|archive-date=23 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923175048/http://www.espnfc.com/story/341697/uzbekistan-and-bahrain-to-play-it-again|url-status=live}}</ref> The replay ended 1–1, and after the return finished 0–0, Uzbekistan were eliminated.

In the [[2007 AFC Asian Cup]], Uzbekistan advanced from the [[2007 AFC Asian Cup Group C|group stage]] by beating [[Malaysia national football team|Malaysia]] 5–0 and [[China PR national football team|China PR]] 3–0. However, Uzbekistan was knocked out of the tournament in the [[2007 AFC Asian Cup knockout stage#Saudi Arabia vs Uzbekistan|quarter-finals]] by losing to [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]] 2–1.{{Citation needed|date=March 2025}}

===2010s===
[[File:Uz Supporters Big Flag.JPG|thumb|right|Uzbekistan national team supporters during a qualification match for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup]] against Japan at [[Pakhtakor Stadium]] in Tashkent]]
After having three foreign coaches (German [[Hans-Jürgen Gede]], Englishman [[Bob Houghton]] and Russian [[Valeri Nepomniachi]]) in three years, the country turned to former Uzbekistan Olympic team coach [[Rauf Inileev]]. During [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification|qualification]] for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup]], Uzbekistan advanced to the [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC fourth round|fourth round]] of the [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)|Asian qualifiers]] after winning their first four matches, but finished last in [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC fourth round#Group A|Group A]] of the final round behind favorites Australia, Japan, Bahrain and Qatar, with four points from eight matches.

[[File:Uzbekistan national football team.jpeg|Uzbekistan at the [[2011 AFC Asian Cup]]|thumb|left|250px]]
In the [[2011 AFC Asian Cup]], Uzbekistan ended in fourth place, their all-time best result in the tournament. After getting past the [[2011 AFC Asian Cup Group A|group stage]] and [[2011 AFC Asian Cup knockout stage#Uzbekistan vs Jordan|quarter-finals]], the Uzbek team lost their first opportunity to reach the Asian Cup final when [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia]] thrashed them 6–0 in the [[2011 AFC Asian Cup knockout stage#Uzbekistan vs Australia|semi-final]] game. Several days later, they were defeated again by [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]] in the [[2011 AFC Asian Cup knockout stage#Third place match|third place match]] 3–2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/match/56036/uzbekistan-vs-south-korea/report|title=Uzbekistan 2–3 South Korea|date=28 January 2011|work=Goal.com|access-date=2 February 2011|archive-date=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140118113037/http://www.goal.com/en/match/56036/uzbekistan-vs-south-korea/report|url-status=live}}</ref>

In [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification|qualification]] for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]], Uzbekistan advanced to Asia's [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC fourth round|fourth round]] after winning their group in the [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC third round#Group C|third round]] over Japan. Uzbekistan finished with 16 points (five wins and one draw), more than any other team in the third round, including an impressive 1–0 away win against Japan. In the fourth round, Uzbekistan finished third in [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC fourth round#Group A|Group A]] behind [[Iran national football team|Iran]] and South Korea, and lost to South Korea (14 points) on goal difference, and would eventually play [[Jordan national football team|Jordan]] in the [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC fifth round|fifth round]] to determine the AFC participant in the [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (inter-confederation play-offs)|intercontinental play-off]]. On 10 September 2013, with the two teams drawn at the end of the second leg, Jordan eventually progressed to the intercontinental play-off after winning 9–8 on [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalties]].

In the [[2015 AFC Asian Cup|2015 Asian Cup]], Uzbekistan advanced to the [[2015 AFC Asian Cup knockout stage|quarter-finals]] after finishing as runners-up in [[2015 AFC Asian Cup Group B|Group B]], won by China. The team was knocked out of the tournament in the [[2015 AFC Asian Cup knockout stage#South Korea vs Uzbekistan|quarter-finals]] after losing 2–0 in [[Overtime (sports)|extra time]] to South Korea.

Uzbekistan continued their quest to head to the World Cup during [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)|2018 FIFA World Cup qualification]], but their campaign had been shattered with a 4–2 defeat to [[North Korea national football team|North Korea]]. However, the Uzbeks soon bounced back and won the last remaining matches to top the group and qualified to the [[2019 AFC Asian Cup]] as well as the last round. Once again, Uzbekistan in the last round, missed an opportunity when they finished fourth, behind Iran, South Korea and [[Syria national football team|Syria]], when Uzbekistan could only manage a 0–0 draw to the South Koreans in the last match.<ref name="espn">{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/video/clip?id=20590948|website=espn.com|title=www.espn.com/video/clip?id=20590948|access-date=28 November 2021|archive-date=1 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181201005308/http://www.espn.com/video/clip?id=20590948|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:TUR-UZB 20190113 Asian Cup 9.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Uzbekistan at the [[2019 AFC Asian Cup]]]]
Uzbekistan started their [[2019 AFC Asian Cup]] campaign with a 2–1 victory over Oman and continued with a 4–0 win over Turkmenistan, which guaranteed Uzbekistan to progress from the group stage for the fifth consecutive time, despite ending with a 1–2 defeat to Japan in the last match. Facing Australia, defending Asian champions, Uzbekistan drew 0–0 after 120 minutes. In the penalty shootout, Australia prevailed with a 4–2 win.

===2020s===
In the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC second round|second qualifying round for the 2022 FIFA World Cup]], Uzbekistan suffered another disappointment by failing to qualify for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC third round|final round]]. The ''White Wolves'' accumulated five wins and three defeats. Moreover, Uzbekistan's failure was also compounded by the fact that [[North Korea national football team|North Korea]], originally in Group H of the same round, surprisingly withdrew due to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], in which FIFA and the AFC then ruled North Korea's results as null and void. This caused [[Lebanon national football team|Lebanon]] to qualify ahead of Uzbekistan, since Lebanon's original results against North Korea were a draw and a loss.<ref>{{cite news|title=South Korea: North Koreans pull out of World Cup qualifying|url=https://apnews.com/article/south-korea-north-korea-world-cup-international-soccer-soccer-fdd6542dd5b1f585b61ca4f3e3fcb167|date=4 May 2021|access-date=7 May 2021|publisher=AP News|archive-date=6 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210506070820/https://apnews.com/article/south-korea-north-korea-world-cup-international-soccer-soccer-fdd6542dd5b1f585b61ca4f3e3fcb167|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the-afc.com/competitions/afc-asian-cup/news/latest-update-on-asian-qualifiers|title=Latest update on Asian Qualifiers|publisher=Asian Football Confederation|date=16 May 2021|access-date=17 May 2021|archive-date=20 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210520215555/https://www.the-afc.com/competitions/afc-asian-cup/news/latest-update-on-asian-qualifiers|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="AFC May update">{{Cite web|url=https://www.the-afc.com/competitions/afc-asian-cup/news/latest-decision-on-asian-qualifiers|title=Latest decision on Asian Qualifiers|publisher=Asian Football Confederation|date=27 May 2021|access-date=6 March 2023|archive-date=2 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210602001057/https://www.the-afc.com/competitions/afc-asian-cup/news/latest-decision-on-asian-qualifiers|url-status=live}}</ref>
[[File:Iran v Uzbekistan 2-2, 25 March 2025, Azadi Stadium, World Cup 2026 qualifier 8.jpg|left|thumb|Uzbekistan squad against [[Iran national football team|Iran]] at the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC third round|third round]] of the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)|2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]].]]
Uzbekistan took part in the [[2023 AFC Asian Cup qualification – third round|third qualifying round for the 2023 AFC Asian Cup]]. Designated as the host country of Group C (due to the [[COVID-19 pandemic in Asia]]), the Central Asians won all three games and finished top of their group without conceding a goal, confirming their qualification for the [[2023 AFC Asian Cup|tournament]]. Uzbekistan was placed in Group B with Australia, Syria and [[India national football team|India]]. Prior to the tournament, Uzbek all-time top goalscorer Eldor Shomurodov sustained a leg injury, ruling him out of the squad. Uzbekistan drew 0–0 in their opening game against [[Syria national football team|Syria]] and won against India 3–0. In their last match against Australia, Uzbekistan drew 1–1 to seal a place in the round of 16 as the second-placed team in their group. They faced Thailand, whom they managed to beat 2–1. In the quarter-finals, they faced hosts Qatar. With the match drawn 1–1 after extra time, Uzbekistan lost 3–2 in the penalty shoot-out.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68193008 |title=Qatar 1-1 Uzbekistan (3-2 on pens): Hosts win penalty shootout to set up Asian Cup semi with Iran |publisher=BBC Sport |date=3 February 2024 }}</ref>

Uzbekistan were unbeaten throughout their entire [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC second round|second qualifying round for the 2026 FIFA World Cup]], winning four matches and drawing two, and entered the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC third round|third qualifying round]] as second place in the group. In the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC third round|third round]], the team qualified for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] for the first time in history, with one match to spare after an away goalless draw with the [[United Arab Emirates national football team|United Arab Emirates]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/uzbekistan-qualify-world-cup-first-time-after-draw-with-uae-2025-06-05/ |title=Uzbekistan qualify for World Cup for first time after draw with UAE |publisher=Reuters |date=5 June 2025 }}</ref> This makes Uzbekistan the first [[Central Asia|Central Asian]] nation, as well as the third former [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet]] republic after [[Russia national football team|Russia]] and [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]], to qualify for the World Cup.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Millar |first=Colin |date=5 June 2025 |title=Uzbekistan, Jordan qualify for World Cup for first time |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6229851/2025/06/05/uzbekistan-world-cup-qualification-2026/ |access-date=5 September 2025 |work=The Athletic |publisher=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>

Uzbekistan entered the [[2025 CAFA Nations Cup]], where the team won the title after a draw against [[Oman national football team|Oman]] and victories over [[Turkmenistan national football team|Turkmenistan]], [[Kyrgyzstan national football team|Kyrgyzstan]] and a last-minute extra-time victory over [[Iran national football team|Iran]] 1–0 in the final.<ref>{{cite news |date=8 September 2025 |title=10-man Iran runners-up at 2025 CAFA Nations Cup |url=https://www.tehrantimes.com/news/517726/10-man-Iran-runners-up-at-2025-CAFA-Nations-Cup |access-date=8 September 2025 |work=Tehran Times |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=9 September 2025 |title=Uzbekistan defeats Iran to win 2025 CAFA Nations Cup |url=https://kun.uz/en/news/2025/09/09/uzbekistan-defeats-iran-to-win-cafa-2025-cup |access-date=9 September 2025 |work=KUN.uz |language=en}}</ref>

